                <head>281. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 6 and 13, <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_RGF1">Reinhardt</persName> exchanged notes for their respective
                    governments acknowledging United States approval in principle of support of a
                    Vietnamese Armed Force of 150,000 in 1956. Included in <persName
                        corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName>’s note of December 6 was a plan for
                    reduction of Vietnamese forces to 150,358 military and 5,319 civilians <pb
                        facs="0630" n="598" xml:id="pg_598"/> by June 30, 1956. In accepting the
                    force structure contained in <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName>’s note,
                        <persName corresp="#p_RGF1">Reinhardt</persName> expressed confidence in his
                    note of December 13 that the Vietnamese Government would continue efforts to
                    reduce the high cost of maintaining its armed forces. Texts of these notes are
                    enclosed in despatch 203 from Saigon, December 27. (Department of State, Central
                    Files, 751G.5–MSP/12–2755)</p>
            </div>
